[normal]Q24 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Faulks:[bold] 
[normal]There is not a lot of legal aid about at the moment, in general terms
[normal]. 
[normal]If I go into a public hospital and I consider myself to be the victim of medical negligence and I have a substantial potential claim, lawyers will not get legal aid to represent me or anybody else in that situation and, if they want to take the case, will only get paid if they are successful
[normal]. 
[normal]That is, so we 
[normal]were told during the course of the last Bill, because of the financial condition of the country
[normal]. 
[normal]Why is judicial review different where the public authority is being challenged
[normal]? 
[normal]I appreciate all that you say about the limited funds available
[normal],
[normal] and I am not suggesting for a moment that the people who do this work are well paid, but why is there a difference?
[normal]Michael Fordham: [bold]In your example, you can take a case on a no win, no fee, but if you win it has an uplift consequence
[normal].
[normal]Lord Faulks:[bold] [bold]No, it does not.
[normal]Michael Fordham: [bold]Well, it depends which case and which model you are operating, but if you are on a CFA that enables you to get paid, you will be able to access an uplift, which can cross
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]subsidise other work that you do
[normal]. 
[normal]What is different about this situation is two things
[normal]. 
[normal]First, these judicial review cases, which in good faith have been judged as viable, where you cannot predict what is going to happen and you cannot be certain or confident that you are going to need or get permission, will not be brought
[normal]. 
[normal]They will not be viable, because legal aid practices will not be able to balance the books if they are not able to be paid for that very important stage of work
[normal]. 
[normal]That is point one
[normal]. 
[normal]Point two—I come back to it—is that public money is spent on both sides in judicial review cases, and I would like somebody to explain, please, why it is that if somebody is spending public money for a good faith judgment of the prospect of success, it is said that they should not be paid if a judge does not agree with them if they act on the claimant side, whereas on the public authority side, they know the importance of effective legal representation, and that means that people should get paid for work that they do, because judicial reviews should be properly argued on both sides.
[normal]Karen Ashton: [bold]Another difference with judicial review, of course, is that the kind of case we are talking about is an event that has happened
[normal];
[normal] it does not change
[normal],
[normal] and therefore 
[normal]you can
[normal] make 
[normal]judgment
[normal]s on the basis of possibility of success and it is very easy to define what success means, which is why you have 
[normal]a 
[normal]conditional fee market
[normal] that has
[normal] developed in relation to private law litigation
[normal]. 
[normal]In judicial review you do not
[normal]; you may well, 
[normal]and this is the problem between issuing and permission
[normal];
[normal] events may overtake the decision that is being challenged
[normal],
[normal] and the case may become academic or may be settled in different ways
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, it is much more difficult for that 
[normal]kind of 
[normal]conditional fee arrangement
[normal],
[normal] with the necessary insurance products that are associated with it
[normal], to work,
[normal] and it has not developed with judicial review
[normal]. 
[normal]It is a very different type of litigation.
[normal]Q25 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Buckland:[bold] [bold]I want to ask Karen
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ashton a further question about the proposal within the 
[normal]c
[normal]onsultation to deal with meritorious claims that are made but are settled before the permission stage is reached
[normal]. 
[normal]There is a proposal there for the LAA to apply some criterion
[normal],
[normal] in its discretion, 
[normal]to 
[normal]make orders where no order for costs has been made
[normal]. 
[normal]What is your view about that proposal
[normal]? 
[normal]Do you think it is a workable solution or do you think it is too narrow?
[normal]Karen Ashton: [bold]There is an inherent problem with it, which is it is after the event and the 
[normal]judgment
[normal]s that we are going to have to make as practitioners are whether we can sustain the financial risk in advance
[normal]. 
[normal]We are going to have to impose, as I say, the decision-making criteria at that earlier stage
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, there is an inherent problem
[normal] in an after-the-
[normal]event 
[normal]discretion, particularly when the Legal Aid Agency already is the body that
[normal] grants the legal aid initially
[normal] on the basis 
[normal]that 
[normal]ha
[normal]s 
[normal]sufficient merit
[normal]—the problem
[normal] 
[normal]is the 
[normal]idea that somehow it would change its mind at a later date and withdraw
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, why can there not be a decision in advance
[normal]? 
[normal]Why does it have to be after the event
[normal]? 
[normal]However, the nature of the particular discretion that is being proposed is on very broad criteria
[normal];
[normal] it involves factors such as late disclosure, which might affect the assessment of your merits beyond the control of the practitioner, and the 
[normal]judgment
[normal] is being made by the very organisation that will have an interest in not paying
[normal]. 
[normal]For all those reasons
[normal],
[normal] I do not think it will be the basis on which practitioners will be able to make 
[normal]judgment
[normal]s on acting that are any better than they would 
[normal]be 
[normal]without the discretion
[normal]. 
[normal]Obviously, it is better than nothing, but I do not think it goes very far in solving the problem.
[normal]The other problem with it is the proposal to assess merit, so there is one factor about assessing the prospect of getting permission, but it is at the point of settlement
[normal]. 
[normal]The reason probably the case is being withdrawn is 
[normal]that 
[normal]something has happened whereby it would be pointless to go to permission
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, the prospects of assessing permission are necessarily going to be low at that point, so it is assessing merit at the wrong point.
[normal]Q26 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Buckland:[bold] 
[normal]I am very grateful
[normal]. 
[normal]In general, do you think that the proposals are going 
[normal]to 
[normal]lead 
[normal]to 
[normal]a situation where agreement of costs between the parties will be encouraged or do you think 
[normal]that 
[normal]it will have the opposite effect
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]in
[normal] that we will have more hearings solely on the issue of costs?
[normal]Karen Ashton: [bold]I think it will go both ways
[normal]. 
[normal]The starting point is there is already an incentive on us to seek and agree costs, because we are already paid at much reduced rates, so
[normal] if we settle with them, there is a great incentive to seek costs;
[normal] it is not that claimant solicitors are not seeking costs
[normal]. 
[normal]Clearly, the same principles on costs would apply, but there will be pressure on claimant solicitors to make the application for costs if they are not going to sort it any other way and there will be ancillary disputes that develop
[normal]. 
[normal]My other concern is 
[normal]that, 
[normal]in discussions to try to get agreement on costs, claimant solicitors are going to be at an unfair disadvantage in those negotiations, because if the alternative is not being paid at all
[normal],
[normal] it seems to me that the public authority defendant could exploit that negotiating position to their advantage
[normal]. 
[normal]In that situation, claimant solicitors could start accepting settlements that are well below the usual rate for payment
[normal].
