[normal]Q32 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Lister of Burtersett:[bold] 
[normal]This question follows on from that and your recommendation that there are 
[normal]quicker
[normal] and more cost
[normal]-
[normal]effective ways of reconciling disputes relating to the 
[normal]public sector equality duty. 
[normal]Can you perhaps expand a bit on how you reached that conclusion and, more importantly, what you consider would be appropriate alternative ways to reconcile disputes relating to 
[normal]the 
[normal]PSED?
[normal]Robert Hayward: [bold]In relation to the first half of your question, Baroness
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lister, can I make an observation
[normal]? 
[normal]What happened was 
[normal]we 
[normal]received evidence in a number of different ways, including going out to meet authorities and other bodies
[normal]. 
[normal]One of the things that struck us when we went out to meet authorities, major authorities
[normal]—
[normal]one major city council and a county counci
[normal]l—
[normal]was how conscious they were of the cases that were going through the process of judicial review and how they tended to freeze decisions
[normal]. 
[normal]As one major city council put it to us, “If we are in the position of either ourselves being taken to judicial review or another local authority where we do the same thing, 
[normal]and that
[normal] in quarter one we are trying to effect £1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million savings, if that takes four quarters to be completed, by the time we get to the fourth quarter we have to make the equivalent of £4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million of savings, which impacts, clearly, four times as much as it would have done had the action been taken in the first 
[normal]quarter
[normal].
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]That is the reason we made the recommendation, because we were struck by councils not only being confronted by their own cases but looking over their shoulder at cases that were applying to other councils; I think we heard that in the previous panel
[normal]. 
[normal]We did not address 
[normal]t
[normal]he second point in relation to ideas
[normal]. 
[normal]There was one barrister on our steering group
[normal]. 
[normal]I am not a lawyer and therefore we made the recommendation that Government should look at it rather than looking at options.
[normal]Q33 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Lister of Burtersett:[bold] 
[normal]T
[normal]his 
[normal]is
[normal] t
[normal]o our other two witnesses, please
[normal]. 
[normal]Do you agree with the steering group’s finding that
[normal], 
[normal]even when decisions are overturned on judicial review due to non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]compliance with the PSED
[normal],
[normal] it is not uncommon for the initial decision to remain unchanged and “it is not clear how this benefits anyone”?
[normal]Helen Mountfield: [bold]There are two answers to that
[normal]. 
[normal]The first is the point that Michael
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fordham made in the previous session that law is about process
[normal]. 
[normal]It is not telling people what the result is
[normal]. I
[normal]t is saying you must think about this
[normal]:
[normal] you must give due—that is, proportionate—regard to it, so that is the appropriate role of the court.
[normal] 
[normal]The second is that I do not recognise that, from the cases that I have done, as the result
[normal]. 
[normal]If I can give you just one or two practical examples
[normal], t
[normal]here was a case in 2008 against Ealing
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Council, which was reconfiguring its domestic violence services in a way that would preclude funding for specialist services for black
[normal] and 
[normal]minority ethnic women
[normal]. 
[normal]That decision was quashed on judicial review for failure to give due regard to equality and the grant funding going forward was reconfigured
[normal]. 
[normal]There have been cases involving dress codes in schools, where a dress code says you just cannot wear a bracelet, when it has been said you have not thought properly about equality for Sikhs
[normal]. 
[normal]That uniform code has been quashed and had to be amended
[normal]. 
[normal]There was a case against Haringey
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Council in 2010 when they made a major planning decision to redevelop an area
[normal]. 
[normal]They had a lot of policy guidance on equality, but they had not applied it to the decision
[normal]. 
[normal]They had not thought about the implications of that decision for small and medium
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]sized enterprises that were largely owned by minority communities in the area
[normal]. 
[normal]That decision was quashed and they had to rethink the planning decision, not because it was a bad decision as a whole to redevelop the area, but because that was a factor that must be taken into account and was taken into account
[normal]. 
[normal]There has been a case in 
[normal]Devon
[normal] about how you set care home fees and they had not thought properly about the additional costs of care for people with dementia
[normal]. 
[normal]Consequently, people with dementia had a smaller choice of private sector provision than others
[normal]. 
[normal]That decision was quashed
[normal] and
[normal] those care home fees were set on a differential basis.
[normal] 
[normal]There have been cases about a taxi licensing decision in Liverpool where they had not appreciated that the taxi they were going to licen
[normal]s
[normal]e that they thought was accessible to all disabled people was not, so they rethought the decision and they made some exceptions to their licensing policy
[normal]. 
[normal]There have been cases in the context of housing where people with mental health difficulties lose their homes as a result of antisocial behaviour
[normal]. C
[normal]ourts, as a result of the 
[normal]public sector equality duty
[normal], will say, before making a possession decision, “Has this person’s community care needs been addressed?” because it may not be proportionate to make them homeless
[normal]—
[normal]street homeless
[normal]—
[normal]in those circumstances if due regard has not been given to their mental health needs.
[normal]That is the practical effect of some of the cases that I am aware of
[normal],
[normal] and the other important effect is that of course litigation is a longstop
[normal]. 
[normal]This is not all about disputes
[normal]. 
[normal]It is about a duty 
[normal]to mainstream thought about equality that, as the courts have said in the past, has played regrettably little role in public sector decision
[normal]-
[normal]making because it has not been enforceable
[normal];
[normal] it has fallen off the end of the to
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]do list
[normal]. 
[normal]The idea, I think, is that you have a duty, the courts explain in quite clear and practical terms what the duty is, that it is enforceable and how it is enforceable, and then decision
[normal]-
[normal]makers feed it into their decision
[normal]-
[normal]making process because they do not want to act unlawfully
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, it has an effect beyond the decided cases
[normal],
[normal] and I am aware of that also from my practice
[normal]:
[normal] that public sector decision
[normal]-
[normal]makers will come and say, “We want to cut this or reconfigure that
[normal]. H
[normal]ow do we do it in a way that ensure
[normal]s
[normal] we take into account relevant considerations?”
[normal] 
[normal]I do not tell them what to do
[normal]. 
[normal]I tell them the sorts of things they need to think about.
[normal]Q34 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Buckland:[bold] 
