[normal]Q35 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Berridge:[bold] 
[normal]Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hammond, can 
[normal]I 
[normal]bring you in at this point
[normal]? 
[normal]What would be the effect, if any, in your view, of the removal of judicial review on the effectiveness of the 
[normal]public sector equality duty? 
[normal]Have you given some thought to what alternative mechanisms, if that were to happen, for enforcing the 
[normal]d
[normal]uty would better ensure that the needs of those people with protected characteristics were taken into account in decision
[normal]-
[normal]making?
[normal]Mark Hammond: [bold]We have given some thought to it but
[normal],
[normal] as Rob has outlined, it is still fairly early days in its consideration
[normal]. 
[normal]We have a number of specific enforcement powers around the PSED, as having broad oversight of it, but we very much view those, as Helen said, as a longstop ourselves
[normal]. 
[normal]Our objective with the PSED is that everyone achieves 
[normal]the
[normal] better policymaking that the 
[normal]d
[normal]uty entails rather than that we are able to say we have managed to take enforcement against A, B and C
[normal]. 
[normal]That is why we have put so much effort into the guidance and advice and encouragement and cajoling that we have with public bodies
[normal]. 
[normal]I can see a slight danger in looking at alternative mechanisms, as the previous panel echoed
[normal]. I
[normal]f one introduced a mandatory judicial review mechanism in between, say, a pre
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]action letter and the courts
[normal],
[normal] that might divert a certain number of cases and reduce a certain amount of cost
[normal]. 
[normal]H
[normal]owever, it would open up a seriou
[normal]s question then as to whether that was mandatory only for those cases that had already qualified, as the previous panel was 
[normal]saying
[normal], or whether you would then need to widen the funnel to those that might not have qualified for a full judicial review because of some factor but ought to qualify for some mandatory mechanism
[normal]. 
[normal]It would be possible to construct mechanisms that ended up costing the public purse more rather than less, depending on how widely that funnel ran.
[normal]Our own powers, as I say, are available on the general duty but are very cumbersome in terms of the pre
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]actions and the terms of referencing that we have to do
[normal]. 
[normal]They are simpler on the specific duties, but they are so narrow that it does not really have any
[normal] real
[normal] impact
[normal]. 
[normal]We would be happy, certainly, to look at a role we might play in some sort of mandatory mechanism, but we would need to look at the powers we have
[normal]. 
[normal]However, we would always argue that it is essential that judicial review does remain as a final option in any instance.
[normal]Q36 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Berridge:[bold] 
[normal]Going back to the first part 
[normal]of
[normal] the question and the other side of the coin, what do you think would be the effect of the removal of judicial review for the equality duty?
[normal]Mark Hammond: [bold]If I put 
[normal]on 
[normal]my previous hat 
[normal]as 
[normal]the Chief Executive of a council, I think it would be that some of the impetus
[normal] or
[normal] imperative to make sure that the decisions we were taking were fully in accordance with the PSED would undoubtedly be lost.
[normal]Helen Mountfield: [bold]Could I just chip in there
[normal]? 
[normal]Before the first modern 
[normal]public sector equality duty
[normal] was 
[normal]introduced, the r
[normal]ace equality duty, there was in fact an equivalent
[normal] but
[normal] only target
[normal] 
[normal]duty on local authorities
[normal],
[normal] and it was never enforced and no
[normal] 
[normal]one was aware of it
[normal]. 
[normal]In that first case, which was brought against the Ministry of Defence in 2005, the reason the Ministry of Defence lost that case was they had simply not given any thought at all to the 
[normal]d
[normal]uty when they were doing something that obviously had serious race implications
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, if you do not have something legally enforceable, people are not aware of it.
[normal] 
[normal]The other important point is that if you took that public law wrong
[normal]—
[normal]you must do this
[normal], 
[normal]but you cannot enforce it legally
[normal]—
[normal]it would be contrary to the rule of law and it would also send a message that giving due regard to equality does not matter anymore; you cannot do anything about it if somebody does not
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, it is an essential mechanism
[normal].
[normal]Q37 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Lister of Burtersett:[bold] 
[normal]I have two questions for Ms
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mountfield
[normal]. 
[normal]You were implicitly partly answering the question 
[normal]in
[normal] your previous answer to me, but in your own experience acting in judicial reviews involving PSED disputes how important have these cases been to the overall equality law framework
[normal]? 
[normal]What do you think would be the potential impact, if any, on protected groups of people if it was not possible to enforce the duty through judicial review?
[normal]Helen Mountfield: [bold]They play an enormously important part in the framework because
[normal],
[normal] of course
[normal],
[normal] since the 1970s brave individuals have been able to take 
[normal]tort claims
[normal] if they think that they have been discriminated against
[normal]. 
[normal]However, that is practically impossible and it does not address structural questions
[normal]. 
[normal]That is why the 
[normal]public sector equality duty
[normal] was introduced in the 
[normal]light of the findings of the Stephen
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lawrence 
[normal]i
[normal]nquiry
[normal]. 
[normal]When Sir
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]William
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Macpherson talked about institutional racism in the police, he was not talking about an institution full of racists
[normal]. 
[normal]He was saying
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]“H
[normal]ere is an institution where the needs of minority ethnic communities have been left out of our thinking
[normal],
[normal] and what this is for is to ensure that we, as public authorities, guard against that future disadvantage
[normal].” 
[normal]Therefore, when it was introduced with all
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]party support, that duty was introduced to ensure that it was no longer just lip
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]service and not the people who make decisions and know what they know just making the decisions as they go, but asking the questions to enable them to identify what we need to do to promote equality of opportunity,
[normal] and
[normal] what we need to do to foster good relations
[normal]. 
[normal]In the first case, Lady
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justice
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Arden 
[normal]in the 
[normal]Elias
[normal] case
[normal] said 
[normal]that 
[normal]this is an integral and important part of the mechanisms for ensuring the aims of anti
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]discrimination legislation
[normal]. 
[normal]My perception, having practised in discrimination law for 20
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]years or so, is that it has had an enormous effect just on awareness of what those aims are and a normative language that these things matter because Parliament has said they are needs
[normal]. 
[normal]We should be trying to do it; this is a useful way of doing it.
[normal] 
[normal]I have said that I think the duties have a practical effect; they are not just red tape
[normal]. 
[normal]They change the way people think over time
[normal]. 
[normal]We are in early days and I agree with Rob
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hayward and his 
[normal]r
[normal]eview that you cannot abolish something until you have seen how it works.
[normal]Q38 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Faulks:[bold] [bold]Ms
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mountfield, you said that you are asked to advi
[normal]s
[normal]e quite often about the 
[normal]public sector equality duty
[normal] and you do not tell the 
[normal]bodies
[normal] what decision to make but tell them how to make it
[normal]. 
[normal]In your experience, do public authorities or those who have to take these decisions find it difficult to interpret what the duty is?
[normal]Helen Mountfield: [bold]I think they find it less difficult in light of the 100
[normal] 
[normal]or so court decisions that have now gone through, particularly the key decisions of the Court of Appeal, because those set out in very clear and practical terms what authorities do
[normal]. 
[normal]They say this is not about filling in a particular form
[normal]. 
[normal]This is not about thinking about the impact of buying air
[normal]-
[normal]conditioning units on transgender people
[normal]. 
[normal]It is about saying what equality effects might this have
[normal]. 
[normal]Let us think about how this might affect people
[normal]. 
[normal]Let us think about what we do not know and let us find out, so that we do give due regard to equality
[normal]. 
[normal]If we are going to reconfigure our libraries so that there are fewer of them, let us address the obvious accessibility issues and see what we can do within the available budget to avoid it having that effect
[normal]. 
[normal]If we are going to have a school uniform policy, let us think about whether it is a policy that is appropriate to foster good race relations or relations between different religious groups
[normal]. 
[normal]What are the issues
[normal]? W
[normal]hat should we be thinking abou
[normal]t? W
[normal]hat information do we need
[normal]? I
[normal]t really is in support of good public sector decision-making and best value and ensuring people are included.
[normal]Q39 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Baroness Lister of Burtersett:[bold] 
[normal]Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hammond
[normal]—
[normal]Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hayward, you might want to comment as well
[normal]—t
[normal]he steering group made recommendations with regard to the role of the 
[normal]c
[normal]ommission, other regulators, inspectorates, and relevant ombudsmen in supporting the implementation of the duty
[normal]. 
[normal]Could you please outline briefly the 
[normal]c
[normal]ommission’s view of its own enforcement role and that of the regulators, inspectorates and relevant ombudsman services?
[normal]Mark Hammond: [bold]Certainly
[normal]. 
[normal]As I started to say in talking to Baroness
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Berridge’s question, our objective in this exercise entirely 
[normal]i
[normal]s that all bodies are abiding by the standards Parliament has said they should
[normal]. 
[normal]We do not count success, as it were, in the number of cases we end up taking
[normal]. 
[normal]In a sense, that is a failure on our part to bring people into compliance
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, the 
[normal]two legs that we have particularly concentrated on are the material we provide to all forms of public authority, both generally on the duty and what is required and with specific sectors and decision
[normal]-
[normal]making
[normal]. 
[normal]That remains a key part of it and, as the 
[normal]r
[normal]eview suggested, we will continue with our board to look at the material we provide and how we can improve that in the light of the feedback we get.
[normal]We also work directly at times both with groups of public bodies, through 
[normal]bodies such as the 
[normal]Local Government Association, 
[normal]and with 
[normal]some of the regulators
[normal]. 
[normal]I was meeting last week with the Chief
[normal] 
[normal]Executive of the Care
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Quality
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Commission, which is a very important partner of ours, talking exactly about how the work they do can pick up our expert input into the sort of assessments they do of how people that they are responsible for are complying
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore, the more that we can work through other regulators, through the forum that we convene among regulators
[normal],
[normal] to ensure that everyone understands what is required for compliance, how that can be done
[normal] and 
[normal]what sort of cases, as Helen said, have come along that might change the view people take
[normal]—
[normal]the more information they are able to have, hopefully, through us
[normal]—
[normal]then the higher the standards they will be able to meet.
